text: don't just rely on that person at your
gym that looks the best because they may
be genetically superior when it comes to
being able to look like that and what
worked for them might not work for you
you really need to pay attention to
technique before anything else just
using a lot of weight doesn't mean
you're gonna get that much stronger if
you're doing it in poor form because
you're not going to get very strong if
you're hurt all the time and I think by
really focusing on form and technique
you engage more of the muscle that
you're really trying to activate in the
first place kind of that mind-muscle
connection if I had to think of what the
second biggest mistake is it's the
opposite into that which is not using
enough weight and is doing set after set
after set and never really pushing
yourself you need to challenge yourself
to the point where you do force the
muscle to get stronger but again don't
go overboard with it where you risk
injury you're really looking for a
weight that you can handle in good form
for the number of repetitions you're
trying to accomplish if somebody's
getting started and they want to gain as
much muscle as possible don't just go by
what you read in the muscle magazines
that these pro bodybuilders are doing
half the time it's not even their real
workout and don't forget they probably
have a lot of other help that you don't
necessarily have in order to help their
muscles grow so when all is said and
done use what works for you but
ultimately don't go overboard with the
weight make sure you have the form down
first
